ANTHRAX - NAMIBIA (13): (BWABWATA NATIONAL PARK) HIPPOPOTAMUS, BUFFALO, OIE
***************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 8 Nov 2017
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2017; 30(45) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=25186


Anthrax, Namibia
----------------
Information received on [and dated] 8 Nov 2017 from Dr Adrianatus Florentius Maseke, Chief Veterinary Officer, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Water and Forestry, Windhoek, Namibia

Summary
Report type: follow-up report No.1, 8 Nov 2017
Date of start of the event: 1 Oct 2017
Date of confirmation of the event: 11 Oct 2017
Report date: 13 Oct 2017
Date submitted to OIE: 13 Oct 2017
Date of previous occurrence: Apr 2017
Reason for notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: _Bacillus anthracis_
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic), necropsy
This event pertains to: a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Mahango, Mbwambwata National Park, Mukwe, Kavango East
Date of start of the outbreak: 27 Oct 2017
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: National Park
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Hippopotamus: _Hippopotamus amphibious_ (Hippopotamidae) / - / 33/ 33 / 0 / 0
African buffalo (Cape buffalo): _Syncerus caffer_ (Bovidae) / - / 16 /16 / 0 / 0

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Hippopotamus: _Hippopotamus amphibious_ (Hippopotamidae) / ** / ** / 100 / **
African buffalo (Cape buffalo): _Syncerus caffer_ (Bovidae) / ** / ** / 100 / **
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter
**Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comment: Mass deaths of hippopotamus were reported in Kavango River, Mahango game reserve of Mbwambwata National Park since 1 Oct 2017. The mass deaths were confirmed by government officials on 7 Oct 2017 by flying over the Kavango River with a helicopter. The Central Veterinary Laboratory confirmed the event by microscopic examination of _Bacillus anthracis_ on 11 Oct 2017. A number of communities and their livestock live in proximity to the game reserve. However, neither human cases nor livestock cases were reported so far. The joint task force consisting of Ministry of Environment, Veterinary Services and Ministry of Health is on the ground.

Control measures
Measures applied: surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; official disposal of carcasses; by-products and waste; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results:
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test Date / Results
Central Veterinary Laboratory (National laboratory) / Hippopotamus / bacteriological examination /23 Oct 2017 / Negative
Central Veterinary Laboratory (National laboratory) / Hippopotamus / microscopic examination / 23 Oct 2017 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-EAFR from HealthMap Alerts
<promed-eafr@promedmail.org>

[This outbreak started on [Sun 1 Oct 2017] in Kavango River, Mahango game reserve of Bwambwata National Park. The outbreak showed mass deaths of over 100 hippopotami. No human or livestock cases have been identified so far. However, on [Mon 23 Oct 2017], a total of 724 people in the Mukwe Constituency received prophylaxis treatment against anthrax as a preventative measure. It is recommended that livestock around the infected areas be vaccinated. - Mod.MMS

This was reported by my colleague MMS in the post:
10 Nov 2017 Anthrax - Namibia (06): (Bwabwata National Park) hippopotamus, buffalo, OIE 20171110.5434947

This is a formal report by Namibia to OIE in Paris confirming what had been reported earlier. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5436447,63256.]
